\section*{Today: Characterization of Trees and Spanning Trees}

A spanning tree is defined next. There are other ways to define trees, including the existence of a unique path between any two vertices or being minimally connected. A graph can also be described as maximally cyclic.

\begin{definition*}
Let $G$ be a connected graph. A spanning tree of $G$ is a tree $T \subseteq G$ such that $V(T) = V(G)$.
\end{definition*}
A spanning tree is formed by taking a connected graph and removing edges until only a tree remains, ensuring all vertices are preserved. Consider a graph representing a network; a spanning tree provides an efficient system where every vertex can be reached using the remaining edges.

